The Lantern Reforms codified the distinction between commercial law (tariff compliance, contract registration) and civic law (militia obligation, tribunal attendance) as separate but overlapping systems administered by different offices.
Before the Reforms, both types of obligation were handled by ward captains who were simultaneously commercial arbiters and militia commanders — a concentration of authority that produced inconsistent outcomes.
The Reforms split these functions: commercial law went to the trade registry offices; civic law went to district watch commanders; disputes between the two systems went to the public tribunal.
The functional split created Midgaard's characteristic bureaucratic complexity — three offices potentially involved in any significant transaction — but also its accountability: each office's decisions were reviewable by the others.
The Continuity faction treats the Lantern Reforms as the governance layer that made Midgaard stable enough to persist through subsequent crises; without standardized infrastructure and legible law, the Ash-and-Iron years' emergency measures would have been applied inconsistently.
The Reckoning faction notes that the Reforms' district boundaries, when combined with the Violet Compact's later registry-primacy principle, created the administrative infrastructure for identifying and processing "unregistered persons" — the eventual mechanism for condemned-debtor transfers.
The lamp-lines' emergency signaling function was repurposed during the Ash-and-Iron period as a population-tracking alert system: specific lantern sequences indicated which districts had unregistered persons requiring intake processing.

