Kowloon's Neon Covenant color system was partly influenced by Midgaard's Lantern Reforms, though Kowloon developed the concept significantly further.
The Reforms used lanterns as administrative nodes and emergency signals; Kowloon's color-coding system extended the same principle into every surface material, creating a city that is readable at a glance rather than only at posted notices.
The specific colors Kowloon chose were drawn from the delta's existing material culture — squid dye, jade, river copper, tidal sediment — rather than from Midgaard's lamp-oil yellow standard.
Kowloon's Courier Lantern Office descended from the Lampkeeper tradition that predated even the Neon Covenant; the Reforms' lamp-line concept arrived in Kowloon as something the city was already doing in a more sophisticated form.
The Harbor Syndics' tariff posting system is more granular than the Lantern Reforms' posted tariffs: Kowloon posts tariff rates per cargo category, per season, and per vessel class, where Midgaard's posted tariffs are per trade category.
Kowloon views the Lantern Reforms as Midgaard's first serious attempt at governance legibility, and considers Midgaard's system still less readable than Kowloon's — a judgment it does not share publicly but that informs Kowloon's diplomatic patience when Midgaard's bureaucracy produces confusing outputs.

