Kiess's founding charter incorporated Lantern Reform infrastructure standards as the baseline for Kiess's own civic legibility requirements, then extended them with formal accountability mechanisms.
The extension was driven by Evermeet's failure: Evermeet had Lantern Reform-equivalent infrastructure but no formal mechanism for officials whose lamp-line decisions were contested to be held accountable.
Kiess's charter requires that every lantern-station equivalent (administrative node) have a posted record of the last five official decisions made at that node — creating a public accountability history at each point in the civic infrastructure.
The posted decision record was designed specifically to prevent the Violet Compact's abuse: if every administrative node's recent decisions are public, the accumulation of sealed-warrant proceedings becomes visible as a pattern rather than remaining as individual acts obscured by procedure.
Kiess's frontier risk doctrine holds that the Lantern Reforms were correct in principle but insufficient in scope: making the system legible to strangers is necessary but not sufficient if the system can still act on strangers without accountability.
The Reform-era lamp-lines' emergency signaling repurposing during the Ash-and-Iron years — to identify districts containing unregistered persons for intake processing — is the specific case Kiess's anti-sealed-warrant doctrine was designed to prevent recurring.

