Rakuen's founding charter adopted Lantern Reform infrastructure standards as part of the institutional modeling on Midgaard's First Stone Accord governance tradition.
The lamp-lines system Rakuen installed during its founding generation was designed to be compatible with Midgaard's standards — an explicit preparation for the annexation that the founding generation expected would eventually occur.
The Southmark Petition's ledger-compliance refusal prompted Rakuen to convert its accounting standards; the accounting conversion brought the ledger system into alignment with Midgaard's Lantern Reform-era registry format.
Rakuen's Bloom Pavilion serves the watched-square function: all civic proclamations, tribunal proceedings, and memorial readings occur there, following the First Stone Accord and Lantern Reform pattern of centralizing civic life at witnessed locations.
The Compact Purist faction views the successive adoptions of Midgaard standards — lamp-lines, accounting, ledger format — as a pattern of institutional concession that yielded nothing: each adoption was followed by a refusal citing different grounds.
The Amendment Track faction views the same adoptions as evidence that Rakuen's institutional infrastructure is now more compatible with Midgaard than Midgaard's constitutional argument acknowledges.

