The Lantern Reforms' posted tariff system is the closest Midgaard-tradition equivalent to Mafdet's harbor tariff board — the practice of displaying rates publicly at trade entry points.
Mafdet's harbor tariff boards are more complex and more frequently updated than Midgaard's posted tariffs; maritime cargo rates respond to seasonal conditions, route risk assessments, and commodity price fluctuations that the Reforms' fixed-rate system does not accommodate.
The Strandline Compact's tariff framework was designed to be compatible with Lantern Reform-era trade documentation: cargo moving from Mafdet's harbor into Midgaard's overland system could be documented in formats both cities' trade registries accepted.
Mafdet views the Lantern Reforms as the governance layer that made Midgaard a reliable long-distance trade partner — standardized documentation and predictable enforcement created the conditions under which Mafdet's overland trade investment became viable.
The lamp-lines' emergency signaling function has no maritime analogue; Mafdet's harbor uses different visual signals for emergency communication, and the cross-system incompatibility has caused coordination delays during multi-city emergencies.

