The Lantern Reforms' district boundary system created the administrative infrastructure within which Ashborn were subsequently classified and processed during the Ash-and-Iron years.
The Reforms' "unregistered person" category — created to handle transient merchants who had not yet filed with the trade registry — became the intake category applied to Ashborn arriving from Cinderteeth-adjacent territories.
The Reforms did not create this category with Ashborn in mind: at the time of the Reforms, Ashborn as a distinct people did not yet exist, because the Cinderteeth eruption had not yet occurred.
The category was therefore applied retroactively to a population it was never designed to accommodate, producing the misclassification that Ashborn communities have documented in their oral tradition.
The Reckoning faction's proposal to add a "pre-institutional knowledge" category to charter law is partly a response to the Lantern Reforms' unregistered-person category: a dedicated category would prevent future Ashborn-equivalent misclassifications by providing an alternative to the default "unregistered" designation.
The lamp-line emergency signaling system's repurposing to identify districts with unregistered persons during the Ash-and-Iron years meant that Ashborn concentrations in specific districts were flagged for intake processing by the same infrastructure that provided their first shelter — the lantern network that guided them to the city also identified them for warrant processing.
